

---------prvisioners--------

1. file-------
 Copies files or directories from your local machine to the target remote resource.
 It typically requires a connection block to define how to access the server (e.g., via SSH or WinRM)
 example--
 txt.html is in your local machine
 copy txt.html to an already existing vm

To use the file provisioner, you need three main blocks:
create the ssh keys first using ssh.keygen

----The resource (your VM)
----The file provisioner
----The connection block (so Terraform knows how to connect to the VM)




2. remote-exec------
 Executes scripts or commands directly on the newly provisioned remote resource. 
 It typically requires a connection block to define how to access the server (e.g., via SSH or WinRM)
 example--
 execute the "sudo apt-get update -y" in the vm
 install a webserver in the vm


3. local-exec
The local-exec provisioner executes a command on the machine where Terraform is running, not inside the VM.

This is useful for tasks like:

Writing the VM's IP to a file
Logging resource details
Calling another script or CLI tool
Sending a notification





#--------resource block---------------
resource "google_compute_instance" "vm1" {

  name         = "vm1"
  machine_type = "e2-micro"
  zone         = "us-central1-a"

  boot_disk {
    initialize_params {
      image = "debian-cloud/debian-12"
    }
  }

  network_interface {
    network = "default"
    access_config {}
  }

  metadata = {
    ssh-keys = "ubuntu:${file("~/.ssh/id_rsa.pub")}"
  }

#-----------connection block----------------
    connection {
      type        = "ssh"
      user        = "ubuntu"
      private_key = file("~/.ssh/id_rsa")
      host        = self.network_interface[0].access_config[0].nat_ip
    }
  }


#-----------provisioner block - file----------------
#copy install.sh file to vm
  provisioner "file" {

    source      = "install.sh"
    destination = "/tmp/install.sh"
  }


#-----------provisioner block - remote -exec----------------
#execute below commands

  provisioner "remote-exec" {

    inline = [
      "echo 'Hello from Terraform'",
      "hostname",
      "uptime",
      "pwd"
    ]
  }


#-----------provisioner block - local-exec----------------
#Print a message after VM creation
#Save the VM's external IP to a file
provisioner "local-exec" {
    interpreter = ["PowerShell", "-Command"]

    command = "Write-Host 'VM Name:' '${self.name}'"
    command = "echo ${self.name},${self.zone},${self.machine_type} >> vm_details.txt"
  }